\section{Introduction and Problem Formulation}

The used-car market represents a complex pricing environment in which vehicle value is shaped by a combination of mechanical, economic, and consumer-driven factors. Unlike new cars, used vehicles vary substantially in mileage, age, condition, and perceived brand reliability, leading to wide price dispersion even among similar models.

The goal of this project is to systematically examine which factors are most strongly associated with used-car prices and to demonstrate the full data science lifecycle, including data cleaning, exploratory visualization, predictive modeling, and statistical inference. A large dataset of online vehicle listings is used to answer four distinct but related research questions.

\subsection{Research Questions}

This analysis addresses the following questions:

\begin{enumerate}
    \item \textbf{Descriptive Question:} What is the average used-car price overall, and how does the average price vary across manufacturers?
    \item \textbf{Exploratory Question:} How is vehicle mileage related to price, and does this relationship differ across vehicle types such as sedans, SUVs, and trucks?
    \item \textbf{Predictive Question:} Can a used carâ€™s price be predicted using observable attributes such as mileage, age, manufacturer, condition, and vehicle type?
    \item \textbf{Inferential Question:} What is the 95\% bootstrap confidence interval for the difference in mean price between Toyota and Honda vehicles?
\end{enumerate}

Each question corresponds to a different stage of analysis and collectively provides a comprehensive view of used-car pricing dynamics.

\section{Data Collection}

The data used in this project come from the \textit{Craigslist Cars \& Trucks} dataset available on Kaggle. The dataset contains hundreds of thousands of used-vehicle listings collected from Craigslist postings across the United States. Each listing includes information such as asking price, odometer reading, vehicle manufacturer, condition, body type, and model year.

This dataset is well-suited for the analysis because it is large, diverse, and contains the key variables needed to support descriptive summaries, exploratory relationship analysis, predictive modeling, and inferential comparisons between manufacturers.

\section{Data Preparation}

\subsection{Cleaning and Filtering}

The raw dataset contains incomplete entries and implausible values that must be addressed prior to analysis. The following data preparation steps were applied:

\begin{itemize}
    \item Listings with missing values for price, odometer, year, manufacturer, condition, or vehicle type were removed.
    \item Listings with prices below \$500 or above \$200{,}000 were excluded to remove unrealistic or erroneous values.
    \item Vehicles with odometer readings below 1{,}000 miles or above 400{,}000 miles were removed.
    \item Vehicles with model years earlier than 1980 or later than 2025 were excluded.
\end{itemize}

These steps ensured that the resulting dataset reflects realistic used-car listings while retaining a large sample size.

\subsection{Feature Engineering}

A new variable, \texttt{age}, was created to represent vehicle age:
\[
\text{age} = 2025 - \text{year}.
\]

Additionally, because used-car prices are highly right-skewed, the natural logarithm of price (\texttt{log\_price}) was computed. This transformation improves numerical stability and makes linear modeling assumptions more reasonable.

After cleaning and feature engineering, the final dataset contained \textbf{197{,}706 observations} and \textbf{8 variables}.

\section{Descriptive Analysis}

\subsection{Overall Price Characteristics}

Across all vehicles in the cleaned dataset, the mean used-car price is \$18{,}820.91, while the median price is \$16{,}495.00. The mean exceeding the median indicates a right-skewed distribution, driven by a smaller number of high-priced vehicles such as luxury cars and newer trucks.

