A strong negative relationship between mileage and price is evident: vehicles with higher mileage tend to sell for lower prices. This pattern is consistent across vehicle types, although trucks and pickups appear to retain higher prices at comparable mileages relative to sedans. This exploratory analysis reveals both general trends and meaningful differences across vehicle categories.

\section{Predictive Analysis}

\subsection{Model Selection and Justification}

To predict vehicle price, a linear regression model was fit using the logarithm of price as the response variable. Predictor variables included odometer reading, vehicle age, manufacturer, vehicle condition, and vehicle type. Linear regression was selected due to its interpretability and its ability to quantify the marginal effects of each predictor.

Categorical variables were encoded using one-hot encoding. All coefficient interpretations are relative to baseline categories omitted during encoding.

\subsection{Model Training and Evaluation}

The dataset was split into training (80\%) and testing (20\%) subsets. Model performance on the test set was evaluated using root mean squared error (RMSE), mean absolute error (MAE), and the coefficient of determination ($R^2$).

\begin{itemize}
    \item RMSE: \$9{,}718.75
    \item MAE: \$6{,}286.04
    \item $R^2$ (log scale): 0.3375
\end{itemize}

These metrics indicate that the model captures a substantial portion of price variability given the limited set of observable features.

\subsection{Interpretation of Results}

Both mileage and vehicle age exhibit negative effects on price, reflecting depreciation over time and usage. Better vehicle condition is associated with higher expected prices, while manufacturer and vehicle type capture systematic brand and market-segment differences. Overall, the model provides a reasonable predictive framework and successfully answers the predictive research question.

\section{Inferential Analysis}

\subsection{Bootstrap Procedure}

To assess uncertainty in manufacturer price differences, a nonparametric bootstrap was used to estimate the difference in mean price between Toyota and Honda vehicles. The sample included 16{,}581 Toyota listings and 10{,}480 Honda listings. For each of 10{,}000 bootstrap iterations, prices were resampled with replacement and the mean difference was computed.

\subsection{Results and Interpretation}

The estimated mean price difference (Toyota minus Honda) is \$5{,}344.73. The 95\% bootstrap confidence interval is:
\[
[\$5{,}097.33,\; \$5{,}586.34].
\]

\begin{figure}[H]
\centering
\includegraphics[width=0.85\textwidth]{figure3_bootstrap.png}
\caption{Bootstrap distribution of the mean price difference between Toyota and Honda vehicles.}
\label{fig:bootstrap}
\end{figure}

Because the confidence interval does not include zero, there is strong statistical evidence that Toyota vehicles have a higher mean price than Honda vehicles in this dataset. This answers the inferential research question by quantifying uncertainty around the estimated difference.

\section{Problem Reformulation and Future Work}

Future work could extend this analysis by incorporating additional vehicle characteristics such as trim level, engine size, accident history, and geographic location. More flexible predictive models, including tree-based or additive models, may improve accuracy. Inferential analyses could also be expanded to examine median price differences or to stratify comparisons by vehicle type.

